			<h4><a id="comment_link_64192548" name="comment_link_64192548" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23206202&amp;cid=64192548" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64192548)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64192548" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64192548); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~WaffleMonster">WaffleMonster</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~WaffleMonster">( 969671 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64192548"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64192548"><p><div class="quote"><p>There is already a solution. Add a Galileo receiver. The Galileo system includes verification of the received data, so it can't be spoofed, using public key crypto.</p><p>If the check fails then assume the signal is spoofed or there is jamming, and fall back to other sensors.</p></div><p>Authenticating signals is great against bored teens with SDRs playing around with GNSS simulators.   When it comes to state actors in a war zone I'm not so sure this is going to stop spoofing.  All you need to do to spoof location is preferentially delay RF signals so that they arrive at your target when you want them to.  There is no requirement to modify the signals in any way.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64192548">

</div>
