<div id="comment_status_64190922" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64190922" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64190922" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64190922" name="comment_link_64190922" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23206202&amp;cid=64190922" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64190922)" >If you are on a large rigid vehicle...</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64190922" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64190922); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Casandro">Casandro</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Casandro">( 751346 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64190922">		
		on Friday January 26, 2024 @05:42PM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23206202&amp;cid=64190922">#64190922</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64190922"><p>... there are actually multiple way to spot simple spoofing.</p><p>Essentially you put multiple GPS receivers on the extreme ends of your vehicle. If spoofing is done by a single transmitter, they will all get the same position, but different times. You can detect this. If spoofing is done by multiple transmitters, each one simulating a satellite, the distances between your GPS receivers will vary widely.</p><p>So essentially you can either use timing-grade GPS receivers and compare their "PPS"-signal, or you can just take the position information from each GPS-receiver and, for example, calculate the distances of them. Those should, within error margins, never change. If there is a simple spoof, those distances will all be zero.</p><p>Since aeroplanes often have wingsspans of 10 meters or more, the precision of the GPS position signal should be good enough to determine if it is "correct" or "zero".</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64190922">
